#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:1
msgid "Contribution Guide"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:3
msgid ""
"Welcome to **SGLang**! We appreciate your interest in contributing. This "
"guide provides a concise overview of how to set up your environment, run "
"tests, build documentation, and open a Pull Request (PR). Whether you’re "
"fixing a small bug or developing a major feature, we encourage following "
"these steps for a smooth contribution process."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:5
msgid "Install SGLang from Source"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:7
msgid "Fork and clone the repository"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:9
msgid ""
"**Note**: New contributors do **not** have the write permission to push to "
"the official SGLang repo. Please fork the repository under your GitHub "
"account, then clone your fork locally."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:11
msgid "git clone https://github.com/<your_user_name>/sglang.git\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:15
msgid "Build from source"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:17
msgid ""
"Refer to [Install SGLang from Source](../get_started/install.md#method-2-"
"from-source)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:19
msgid "Format code with pre-commit"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:21
msgid ""
"We use [pre-commit](https://pre-commit.com/) to maintain consistent code "
"style checks. Before pushing your changes, please run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:23
msgid ""
"pip3 install pre-commit\n"
"pre-commit install\n"
"pre-commit run --all-files\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:29
msgid ""
"**`pre-commit run --all-files`** manually runs all configured checks, "
"applying fixes if possible. If it fails the first time, re-run it to ensure "
"lint errors are fully resolved. Make sure your code passes all checks "
"**before** creating a Pull Request."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:30
msgid ""
"**Do not commit** directly to the `main` branch. Always create a new branch "
"(e.g., `feature/my-new-feature`), push your changes, and open a PR from that "
"branch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:31
msgid ""
"Link checking with lychee is **enforced in CI**. By default, it is not "
"blocking local commits."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:32
msgid ""
"To run local link checks manually, use: `pre-commit run --hook-stage manual "
"lychee --all-files`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:34
msgid "Run and add unit tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:36
msgid ""
"If you add a new feature or fix a bug, please add corresponding unit tests "
"to ensure coverage and prevent regression."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:38
msgid "Unit tests (no server required)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:40
msgid ""
"Unit tests live under [`test/registered/unit/`](https://github.com/sgl-"
"project/sglang/tree/main/test/registered/unit), organized to mirror the "
"`python/sglang/srt/` source tree. These tests validate component logic "
"**without** launching a server or loading real model weights. SGLang uses "
"Python's built-in [unittest](https://docs.python.org/3/library/unittest."
"html) framework with [pytest](https://docs.pytest.org/) as the test runner."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:43
msgid ""
"**When to add a unit test:** If you modify a file under `python/sglang/srt/"
"`, check whether a corresponding test exists in `test/registered/unit/` and "
"add coverage for your changes. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:45
msgid ""
"srt/mem_cache/radix_cache.py   →  unit/mem_cache/test_radix_cache.py\n"
"srt/sampling/sampling_params.py →  unit/sampling/test_sampling_params.py\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:50
msgid "**Run unit tests locally:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:52
msgid ""
"pytest test/registered/unit/ -v                # all unit tests\n"
"pytest test/registered/unit/mem_cache/ -v      # one module\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:57
msgid "**Run with coverage:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:59
msgid "pytest test/registered/unit/ --cov --cov-config=.coveragerc -v\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:63
msgid ""
"For conventions on CI registration, test structure, and examples, see [`test/"
"registered/unit/README.md`](https://github.com/sgl-project/sglang/tree/main/"
"test/registered/unit/README.md)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:65
msgid "E2E tests (server required)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:67
msgid ""
"For tests that require launching a server, refer to [`test/registered/README."
"md`](https://github.com/sgl-project/sglang/tree/main/test/registered/README."
"md) for guidance on where to place your test."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:69
msgid ""
"For detailed instructions on running tests and integrating them into CI, "
"refer to [test/README.md](https://github.com/sgl-project/sglang/tree/main/"
"test/README.md)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:71
msgid "Write documentations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:73
msgid ""
"We recommend new contributors start from writing documentation, which helps "
"you quickly understand SGLang codebase. For more details, please refer to "
"[docs/README.md](https://github.com/sgl-project/sglang/tree/main/docs/README."
"md)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:76
msgid "Test the accuracy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:77
msgid ""
"If your code changes the model output, please run the accuracy tests. A "
"quick sanity check is the few-shot GSM8K."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:79
msgid ""
"# Launch a server\n"
"python3 -m sglang.launch_server --model Qwen/Qwen2-7B-Instruct\n"
"\n"
"# Evaluate\n"
"python3 -m sglang.test.few_shot_gsm8k --num-questions 200\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:87
msgid ""
"Please note that the above script is primarily a sanity check, not a "
"rigorous accuracy or speed test. This test can have significant variance (1%–"
"5%) in accuracy due to batching and the non-deterministic nature of the "
"inference engine. Also, do not rely on the \"Latency/Output throughput\" "
"from this script, as it is not a proper speed test."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:91
msgid ""
"GSM8K is too easy for state-of-the-art models nowadays. Please try your own "
"more challenging accuracy tests. You can find additional accuracy eval "
"examples in:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:93
msgid ""
"[test_eval_accuracy_large.py](https://github.com/sgl-project/sglang/blob/"
"main/test/registered/eval/test_eval_accuracy_large.py)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:94
msgid ""
"[test_gpt_oss_1gpu.py](https://github.com/sgl-project/sglang/blob/main/test/"
"registered/core/test_gpt_oss_1gpu.py)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:96
msgid "Benchmark the speed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:97
msgid ""
"Refer to [Benchmark and Profiling](../developer_guide/"
"benchmark_and_profiling.md)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:99
msgid "Requesting a review for merge"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:100
msgid ""
"You can follow the pull request merge process described in [MAINTAINER.md]"
"(https://github.com/sgl-project/sglang/blob/main/.github/MAINTAINER.md). You "
"will need to work with the Merge Oncall, Codeowner, and other reviewers to "
"get their approvals. Then your PR can be merged."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:104
msgid "How to Trigger CI Tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:106
msgid ""
"We have a lot of open PRs but limited CI machines, so only top and trusted "
"contributors have permission to trigger CI tests. Users with permission are "
"listed in the [CI_PERMISSIONS.json](https://github.com/sgl-project/sglang/"
"blob/main/.github/CI_PERMISSIONS.json)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:109
msgid ""
"**PR authors** can always use `/rerun-failed-ci` on their own PRs, even if "
"they are not listed in `CI_PERMISSIONS.json`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:111
msgid ""
"For CI to run on a pull request, it must have the \"run-ci\" label. "
"Authorized users can add the label or rerun failed tests by commenting on "
"the PR with one of these commands:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:113
msgid ""
"`/tag-run-ci-label`: Adds the \"run-ci\" label. Every future commit will "
"trigger CI."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:114
msgid ""
"`/rerun-failed-ci`: Reruns the failed or flaky tests from the most recent "
"commit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:115
msgid ""
"`/tag-and-rerun-ci`: A single command that performs both `/tag-run-ci-label` "
"and `/rerun-failed-ci`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:116
msgid ""
"`/rerun-stage <stage-name>`: Reruns a specific test stage without waiting "
"for its dependencies. This is useful when you want to quickly validate a fix "
"for a specific test failure instead of waiting ~30 minutes for preceding "
"stages to complete."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:118
msgid ""
"If you have permission, the [Slash Command Handler](https://github.com/sgl-"
"project/sglang/actions/workflows/slash-command-handler.yml) will run your "
"command and react with a 👍 to your comment. It may take up to a few minutes "
"for the reaction to appear. Here’s a usage [example](https://github.com/sgl-"
"project/sglang/pull/14253#issuecomment-3599509302)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:120
msgid ""
"To avoid spamming a PR with too many `/rerun-failed-ci` comments, you can "
"also trigger the command by editing an existing comment and adding any "
"suffix (e.g., `/rerun-failed-ci try again`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:122
msgid ""
"Example of rerunning a single test stage: `/rerun-stage unit-test-backend-4-"
"gpu`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:124
msgid ""
"If you don’t have permission and you’re not the PR author, please ask "
"maintainers to trigger CI for you."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:126
msgid "CI rate limits"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:128
msgid ""
"Due to CI scheduling and limited resources, higher-priority PRs may preempt "
"running jobs. In such cases, you may need to rerun the tests. We apply CI "
"rate limits to prevent abuse and ensure fair usage of our CI resources."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:131
msgid ""
"Each CI workflow has a default limit defined in its workflow configuration "
"file. For example, in [pr-gate.yml](https://github.com/sgl-project/sglang/"
"blob/main/.github/workflows/pr-gate.yml), the default cooldown period is 120 "
"minutes, and each workflow can override it via the `cool-down-minutes` input "
"parameter:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:133
msgid ""
"cool-down-minutes:\n"
"  description: \"Default cooldown period in minutes; 0 disables rate "
"limiting\"\n"
"  type: number\n"
"  default: 120\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:140
msgid ""
"Users listed in [CI_PERMISSIONS.json](https://github.com/sgl-project/sglang/"
"blob/main/.github/CI_PERMISSIONS.json) may have a per-user cooldown "
"interval. In practice, we use the minimum of the workflow’s default window "
"and the user-specific interval."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:142
msgid "Code style guidance"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:143
msgid ""
"Avoid code duplication. If the same code snippet (more than five lines) "
"appears multiple times, extract it into a shared function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:144
msgid ""
"Minimize device synchronization. Reduce expensive CPU-GPU synchronization "
"operations, such as `tensor.item()` or `tensor.cpu()`, whenever possible. "
"Use vectorized code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:145
msgid ""
"Prioritize extreme efficiency. SGLang is a runtime, and most of your code "
"runs on the critical path for every request. Optimize all minor overheads as "
"much as possible, especially in the model forward code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:146
msgid ""
"A common pattern is some runtime checks in the model forward pass (e.g., "
"[this](https://github.com/sgl-project/sglang/blob/"
"f1b0eda55c2c4838e8ab90a0fac7fb1e3d7064ab/python/sglang/srt/models/"
"deepseek_v2.py#L486-L491)). These are very likely the same for every layer. "
"Please cache the result as a single boolean value whenever possible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:147
msgid ""
"Make functions as pure as possible. Avoid in-place modification of arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:148
msgid ""
"Keep files concise. If a file exceeds 2,000 lines of code, split it into "
"multiple smaller files. (e.g., `scheduler.py`, "
"`scheduler_output_processor_mixin.py`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:149
msgid "Keep tests run fast."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:150
msgid ""
"If a single test file run longer than 500 seconds, split it into multiple "
"smaller files (e.g., `test_eagle_infer_a.py`, `test_eagle_infer_b.py`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:151
msgid ""
"If a single job in a github workflow runs longer than 30 mins, split it into "
"smaller jobs/steps."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:152
msgid "Reuse server launches in your unit tests to make tests run faster."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:153
msgid ""
"Never use `pickle.loads()`, `pickle.load()`, or `recv_pyobj()` to "
"deserialize untrusted or network-received data. Python's [pickle module is "
"not secure](https://docs.python.org/3/library/pickle.html) — it can execute "
"arbitrary code during deserialization. Use safe serialization formats such "
"as [msgpack](https://github.com/jcrist/msgspec) or JSON instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:154
msgid "When supporting new hardware or features, follow these guidelines:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:155
msgid "Do not drastically change existing code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:156
msgid ""
"Always prefer new files to introduce specific components for your new "
"hardware (e.g., `allocator_ascend.py`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:157
msgid ""
"If you write multiple if/else blocks for new features, ensure the common "
"path (e.g., NVIDIA hardware or the existing code path) is the first branch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:159
msgid "How to update sgl-kernel"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:160
msgid ""
"Since sglang and the `sglang-kernel` (prior `sgl-kernel`) distribution are "
"separate Python packages, our current GitHub CI infrastructure does not "
"support updating a kernel and using it immediately within the same pull "
"request (PR). To add a new kernel or modify an existing one in the `sgl-"
"kernel/` source tree, you must use multiple PRs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:163
msgid "Follow these steps:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:165
msgid ""
"Submit a PR to update the sgl-kernel source code without using it in sglang "
"python package (e.g., [#8884](https://github.com/sgl-project/sglang/"
"pull/8884/files))."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:166
msgid ""
"Bump the version of the kernel package (e.g., [#9220](https://github.com/sgl-"
"project/sglang/pull/9220/files))."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:167
msgid ""
"Once merged, this will trigger an automatic release of the `sglang-kernel` "
"wheel to PyPI."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:168
msgid ""
"If not urgent, you can wait for other people to release the wheel. A new "
"version will typically be released within one week."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:169
msgid "Apply the changes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:170
msgid ""
"Update the `sglang-kernel` version in `sglang/python/pyproject.toml` to use "
"the modified kernels."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:171
msgid "Update the related caller code in the sglang to use the new kernel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:173
msgid "Tips for newcomers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide/contribution_guide.md:175
msgid ""
"If you want to contribute but don’t have a specific idea in mind, pick "
"issues labeled [“good first issue” or “help wanted”](https://github.com/sgl-"
"project/sglang/issues?"
"q=is%3Aissue+label%3A%22good+first+issue%22%2C%22help+wanted%22). These "
"tasks typically have lower complexity and provide an excellent introduction "
"to the codebase."
msgstr ""

